<font color="#FF0000">MEMORIES OF THE NIGHT</font><br>
<tt>Wed Oct 15 20:22:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
MTF and Sparrowhawk,<br><br>
Your are right.  The gift keeps on giving.  I knew when I read the post it might be ones of those with triggers.  It actually brought what I call the quiet times to me.  No pain, but a definite need for absolute solitude.  The need to drift back and pay tribute.  I always hated the SAR times.<br><br>
The radio transmissions are still clear in my head.  Beeper, Beeper come up voice.  Sometimes Charlie's voice.  I really hated the times when the guys wanted to dictate messages to the family.  The hot mike times when they felt someone's voice would keep them from dying alone.  For one tour I worked the airborne signal booster.  Let you guys use the UHF/VHF without range problems.  Always working deep north.  As we use to say, &quot;To hell 300 miles beyond and back&quot;.  Into China when it was necessary.  They didn't like that of course, but when all hell was breaking loose the GCI site (usually Red Crown) would call in the clear, &quot;My weapon is off the Air.&quot;  That was time to do anything that was necessary including flying into those forbidden zones.  To be officially caught was instant punishment.  What a bitch.  Always returning with the fuel low level light on just to make sure you didn't pad yourself at someone else's expense.<br><br>
Rolling all the freqs looking for calls.  I can't write down the conversations, I don't want to remember and some I can't forget.  I used to come back at night to make sure there was someone to talk to.  Actually pulled off some stateside phone patches when the time was right.  They never knew our name.  We weren't important they were.<br><br>
It is time to stop.  I am beginning to remember more.  Back to the quiet times.<br><br>
My honor was to have served.<br>

<p><code>--   (SW) </code><p>


